Introduction

Since 5 years ago, the teams compeeting at NBA have implemented powerful data analytics strategies in their teams and data analytics is currently the basis for decision making in the league. From transfers to style of play all decision making processes in the NBA are influenced by data analysis.

Several articles were published in the last years explaining and proving how the implementation of data analytics changed not only high leve decisions but also the style of play. Some studies even suggest that the teams are getting less interested in a different type of players than before.

This attracted us to the topic and we wanted to use the available data from different data sources (NBA official API, specialised websites and Kaggel databases) to answer some common questions an bust some myths about the NBA and basketball in general.

paragraphs.text:
%md
We used data from 3 main data sources:
    1. NBA official API
    2. Kaggel
    3. Hoopshype.com
#### 1. NBA official API
It has been very complicated to work with the official API. The level of complexity and number of endpoints along with the specialised language used in NBA increased the difficulty of finding the right data to solve the questions we wanted to solve. Additionally,the API limited the requests to around 15 per IP in a certain period of time without issuing any error message, therefore we did not realise we were not retrieving data after some time. To overcome the limit of requests, we tried to use a method by utilising different proxies but it didn't work either. Finally we could retrieve all the needed information using a mobile data service as it provides a dynamic IP and the NBA API system was not banning us.
Finally, from this data source we obtained the tables 'players','teams' and performance.

#### 2.Kaggel
Kaggel is a data science community providing resources for data analytics. From this website we could find a historical record of the players' salaries. We used this information to complement the 'salaries' table in our DB.

#### 3. Hoopshype.com
Hoops Hype is a basketball specialised website that contains several information on the league. We used webscrapping to obtain the salaries' information for all active players for the current and future seasons.

Player level

* Weight has a positive effect on rebounds
* The players that score more points are better paid, but not the ones that have a higher positive impact on the game
* Height has no effect on any performance metric

Team level

* The number of assists have a positive effect on points (a bit stronger than at individual level)
* The number of rebounds has a positive effect on the points achieved (very similar than at individual level)
* Usually, non-US players perform slightly better than US players

* Highest positive correlation between assist and points (0.683074)
* Also high positive corr. between rebounds and points (0.665074)
* Considering that PIE = What you do (season) / what happens in the game, and What you do = x + 1*PTS + 1.5*RBS + 1*AST. We can see that:

The weight of PTS > weight of AST in the correlation but not in the formula
